nternational Symposium'', Athens, Greece September 1973. Proceedings edited by A. Panayiotopoulos (Greek Mathematical Society) 1975. [http://www.hms.gr/apothema/?s=scf&i=29 Online]\n* Conference on ''Advances in Convex Analysis and Global Optimization (Honoring the memory of C. Carath\u00e9odory)'' June 5\u20139, 2000, Pythagorion, Samos, Greece. [http://www.samos.aegean.gr/math/acago Online].\n* International Congress: ''Carath\u00e9odory in his ... origins'', September 1\u20134, 2000, Vissa Orestiada, Greece. Proceedings edited by Thomas Vougiouklis (Democritus University of Thrace), Hadronic Press FL USA, 2001. {{isbn|1-57485-053-9}}.\n\n== External links ==\n* {{MacTutor Biography|id=Caratheodory}}\n* {{in lang|el}} [http://www.karatheodori.gr/ Web site dedicated to Carath\u00e9odory]\n* {{in lang|el}} [http://www.s-karatheodoris.gr  club www.s-karatheodoris.gr]\n* {{MathGenealogy |id=7517}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Caratheodory, Constantin}}\n[[Category:1873 births]]\n[[Category:1950 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century mathematicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century German mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Greeks of the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:German people of Greek descent]]\n[[Category:Greek mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox Christians from Germany]]\n[[Category:Complex analysts]]\n[[Category:Mathematical analysts]]\n[[Category:Members of the Prussian Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:Thermodynamicists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Berlin]]\n[[Category:People from Brussels]]\n[[Category:Occupation of Smyrna]]\n[[Category:University of G\u00f6ttingen alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Academy of Athens (modern)]]\n[[Category:Variational analysts]]\n[[Category:Mathematicians involved with Mathematische Annalen]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Constantin_Carath%C3%A9odory"}
{"title_page": "Connecticut Military Department", "text_new": "{{short description|Component of the US National Guard of the state of Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name   = Connecticut Military Department\n|logo          = [[File:Coat of Arms of the State of Connecticut.jpg|200px]]\n|logo_width    = \n|logo_caption  = Coat of arms of the state of Connecticut\n|seal          = \n|seal_width    = \n|seal_caption  = \n|formed        = 1939\n|preceding1    = \n|dissolved     = \n|superseding   = \n|jurisdiction  = [[Connecticut]]\n|headquarters  = [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford, CT]]\n|region_code   = \n|employees     = \n|budget        = \n|minister1_name  = \n|minister1_pfo   = \n|minister2_name  = \n|minister2_pfo   = \n|chief1_name     = Major General [[Francis J. Evon, Jr.|Francis J. Evon]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ng.mil/ngbgomo/library/bio/862.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805110716/http://www.ng.mil/ngbgomo/library/bio/862.htm |archive-date=2009-08-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|chief1_position = [[Connecticut Adjutant General|The Adjutant General]], Connecticut National Guard\n|chief2_name     = \n|chief2_position = \n|parent_department =\n|parent_agency = \n|child1_agency = [[Connecticut State Militia]]\n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n|map       = \n|map_width = \n|map_caption = \n}}\nThe '''Connecticut Military Department''' is a state agency of the government of [[Connecticut]]. Its primary components are the \n[[Connecticut Army National Guard]], the [[Connecticut Air National Guard]], and four companies of the state militia. The Military Department of the [[State of Connecticut]] traces its origins to May 11, 1637, when the \"General Courts\" (colonial assembly - legislature) established a military arm of the provincial government. In 1939, the State's Military Department. was established to consolidate the offices of  [[Adjutant General]], [[Quartermaster General]], [[Armory (military)|Armory Board]], and Armory Board Inspector.<ref>per 1939 CGS Cum Suppl. sec. 215e. Military Dept. directs the Adjutant General.</ref>\n\n==Mission==\nThe Military Department of the State of Connecticut's principle public responsibility is to serve as the protector of American citizens of the State and their property in time of war, invasion, rebellion, riot or disaster. It serves as the main resource for the [[Governor of Connecticut|Governor]] in ensuring public safety in a variety of emergencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1345&q=257166|title=CT Military Department Agency Information|publisher=CT Military Department|accessdate=24 December 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113230443/http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1345&q=257166|archivedate=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Connecticut National Guard as the state militia also has a Federal Constitutional mission to support the [[President of the United States]] as Commander-in-Chief of the [[United States Armed Forces|Armed Forces of the United States]] and the [[United States Government|Federal Government]] in times of War or National Emergencies.\n\n==Components==\n\n===[[Connecticut National Guard]]===\nThe [[United States Constitution|Constitution of the United States]] specifically grants the U.S. Congress the power to \"raise armies.\" The U.S. Army, Navy, Air Force are armies raised under this provision. Additionally, the States, under the 2nd and 10th Amendments, have the right to raise their own armies, historically known as militias, today known as a State Defense Force (SDF). After the civil war, many states reduced funding for their militias and military training programs causing the threat of a reduction in war preparedness. As a result, Congress decided to raise a new federal army to be jointly administered by the states alongside the state defense forces: that army is known as the [[National Guard of the United States]]. Like the state militia/SDF, the National Guard is typically administered by the governors. Unlike the militia/SDF, the National Guard may be deployed abroad without the permission of the state governor, whereas the militia/SDF is under the exclusive authority of the states except in the rare event of invasion of the United States or domestic insurrection as specified in Article I Section 8 of the U.S. Constitution.\n\nThe Federal mission assigned to the National Guard is: \"To provide properly trained and equipped units for prompt mobilization for war, National Emergency or as otherwise needed.\"\n\nThe state mission assigned to the National Guard is \"To provide trained and disciplined forces for domestic emergencies or as otherwise provided by state law.\"\n \nThe Connecticut National Guard bestows a number of decorations for services to or on behalf of the state.\n\nMajor General [[Francis J. Evon, Jr.]] is the current [[Connecticut Adjutant General]] (TAG).\n\n====Connecticut Army National Guard====\nThe Connecticut Army National Guard was originally formed in 1672. During the [[War of 1812]], the [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] state government refused to place the state militia under control of the [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] national government, which resulted in friction, especially following British attacks on [[New London, Connecticut|New London]] and [[Stonington, Connecticut|Stonington]].\n\nAfter the American Civil War came to an end in 1865, a segregated company was raised in the Fifth battalion of the Connecticut National Guard so that men of color in [[New Haven]] could serve their state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015483/1882-08-09/ed-1/seq-2/|title=Presentation: Company A, Fifth Battalion, Presented with a Life Size Portrait of Captain J. H. Wilkins - Remarks of Ex and Present Officers|publisher=Morning Journal and Courier|website=Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers. Library of Congress.|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Company A (1870-1919<ref>{{cite book|last=Saunders|first=Ernest|title=Blacks in the Connecticut National Guard: A Pictorial and Chronological History 1870 to 1919|date=1977|publisher=New Haven Afro-American Historical Society|publication-place=New Haven, Connecticut}}</ref>), bearing throughout its service monikers to honor its primary instigator, James H. Wilkins<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Wilkins-4037|title=Major James H. Wilkins|website=WikiTree|last=Raymoure|first=K|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> - a sergeant with the famous [[54th_Massachusetts_Infantry_Regiment|54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]] during the Civil War who bore the national flag at the [[Battle of Olustee]] - was also known as the ''Wilkins Guard''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84027718/1900-03-22/ed-1/seq-3/|title=Obituary of James H. Wilkins|publisher=Connecticut Western News|website=Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers. Library of Congress.|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>, the ''Wilkins Old Guard'', and the ''Wilkins Tigers''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ctdigitalnewspaperproject.org/2016/09/african-americans-in-the-ct-national-guard-1870-to-1919/|title=African Americans in the CT National Guard, 1870 to 1919|author=CT|website=Connecticut Digital Newspaper Project|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Militia Act of 1903]] organized the various [[U.S. state|state]] [[militia]]s into the present National Guard system.\n\nThe 102d Infantry Regiment fought with the [[26th Infantry Division (United States)|26th Infantry Division]] in World War I and then served with the [[43rd Infantry Division (United States)|43d Infantry Division]] from 1924 to 1951-52, including [[World War II]] and a deployment to [[West Germany]] during the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/1-102in.htm|title=1st Battalion, 102nd Infantry Regiment|first=John|last=Pike|website=www.globalsecurity.org|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426182812/https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/1-102in.htm|archivedate=26 April 2018}}</ref> Other major historical regiments of Connecticut were the [[169th Infantry Regiment (United States)|169th Infantry Regiment]] and 192d Field Artillery.\n\nAfter 1968, the main formation in the state became the 43d Infantry Brigade of the [[26th Infantry Division (United States)|26th Infantry Division]].\n\nToday, the Connecticut Army National Guard is composed of approximately 5,000 soldiers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070128164746/http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/ |archivedate=2007-01-28 }}</ref>   It maintains facilities in 22 communities.  In 1999, these facilities included 22 armories, eight maintenance shops, four aviation facilities, four training site facilities.\n\nIts units include the 85th Troop Command, 143rd Area Support Group, 14th Civil Support Team (WMD), 248th Engineer Company, 250th Engineer Company, 143d and 643d Military Police Companies, 141st and 142d Medical Companies, the 143d Combat Service Support Battalion (formerly FSB), the 1109th Aviation Depot (AVCRAD), the 169th Regiment (RTI), and the [[192nd Military Police Battalion|192d Military Police Battalion]]. The primary combat unit is the 1st Battalion, 102d Infantry Regiment, assigned to the [[86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team (United States)|86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team]], which is headquartered in [[Vermont]].\n\n'''Aviation'''\n\nOne base is the Army Aviation Support Facility at [[Bradley International Airport]] where the 1st Battalion, 169th Aviation Regiment operate the CH-47F, UH-60A/L, HH-60M & C-12U<ref>https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/DAS/Communications/Communications-List-Docs/Digest/Digest-2015-2016/Military-Department.pdf</ref> The unit also operates Detachment 2, Company C, 3d Battalion, [[126th Aviation Regiment (United States)|126th Aviation Regiment]] (HH-60M)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20180610/nws09/180619946|title=New Connecticut National Guard medical helicopter unit set to deploy to Southwest Asia|publisher=The Day|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> and Company B, 2d Battalion (General Support), [[104th Aviation Regiment (United States)|104th Aviation Regiment]] (CH-47F)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ct.ng.mil/News/Pages/Connecticut-Army-National-Guard-Sends-Troops,-CH-47s-to-Support-Relief-Efforts.aspx|title=Connecticut Army National Guard Sends Troops, CH-47s to Support Relief Efforts|publisher=Connecticut National Guard|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====[[Connecticut Air National Guard]]====\n[[File:C-27J and C-21A of Connecticut ANG 2010.jpg|thumb|right|A C-21A of the Connecticut Air National Guard sits beside a C-27 during an Alenia familiarisation visit to Bradley ANGB]]\nThe [[Connecticut Air National Guard]] traces its history back to [[World War I]] with the beginnings also of the [[United States Army Air Service]]. It comprises approximately 1,200 airmen and officers assigned to the [[103d Airlift Wing|103rd Airlift Wing]] and 103rd Air Control Squadron. The [[103d Airlift Wing|103rd Airlift Wing]] is  based in [[East Granby, Connecticut|East Granby]] at the Bradley Air National Guard Base at [[Bradley International Airport]].\n\n[[File:F-100D 118th TFS Connecticut ANG 1976.JPEG|thumb|right|An F-100 of the Connecticut Air National Guard, 1976]]\nKnown as the \"Flying Yankees\", the [[103d Airlift Wing|103rd Airlift Wing]] is the third-oldest [[Air National Guard]] unit in the United States with a history dating back to World War I.<ref>Governor M. Jodi Rell (CT) (10 August 2005). [http://www.ct.gov/governorrell/cwp/view.asp?Q=300044&A=1761 Governor Rell Visits National Guard Fighter Wing Targeted Under BRAC Process] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519170516/http://www.ct.gov/governorrell/cwp/view.asp?Q=300044&A=1761 |date=2011-05-19 }} Press Release.</ref> Until 2008, the organization was known as the 103rd Fighter Wing (103 FW), operationally gained by the [[Air Combat Command]] (ACC) and equipped with [[A-10 Thunderbolt]] aircraft.  As a result of [[Base Realignment and Closure]] (BRAC) actions, the wing's A-10 fighter aircraft were reassigned to other units and the 103rd reequipped with [[C-21 Learjet]] aircraft as a \"placeholder\" flying mission under the Air National Guard's VANGUARD<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oai.dtic.mil/oai/oai?verb=getRecord&metadataPrefix=html&identifier=ADA454806 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717145048/http://oai.dtic.mil/oai/oai?verb=getRecord |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> program until the 103rd's next flying mission could be determined.  Following this change in mission, the unit was redesignated the 103rd Airlift Wing and placed under the operational claimancy of [[Air Mobility Command]] (AMC).\n\nThe 103rd Air Control Squadron is based in [[Orange, Connecticut]],<ref name=CTANGSITE>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctbrad.ang.af.mil/ourmission.html |title=Our Mission |accessdate=2007-07-17 |work=Connecticut Air National Guard |publisher=U.S. Air Force |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709094444/http://www.ctbrad.ang.af.mil/ourmission.html |archivedate=2007-07-09 }}</ref> and is known as \"Yankee Watch\". The mission of the 103rd Air Control Squadron is real-time detection, identification and surveillance of air traffic for combat operations and [[homeland defense]].  The 103rd ACS is the oldest unit of its kind in the United States military.<ref name=\"CTANGSITE\"/>\n\nThe Connecticut Air National Guard counts one [[astronaut]] amongst its former members, [[Jack Swigert]], who flew on [[Apollo 13]]. Swigert served with the CT ANG from April 1960 to October 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html |title=Biographical Data - John L. Swigert, Jr. |accessdate=2007-07-19 |author=Astronaut Office of the Johnson Space Center |date=January 1983 |work=Johnson Space Center - Astronaut Biographies |publisher=NASA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320052948/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html |archivedate=2007-03-20 }}</ref>\n\nBrigadier General Daniel L Peabody is the current Assistant Adjutant General-Air, for the CT ANG.\n\n===Connecticut State Guard===\nThe Connecticut State Guard is the organized militia portion of the state military. As a [[State Defense Force]] it is a military entity authorized by both the State Code of Connecticut and Executive Order. The State Defense Force (SDF) is the state\u2019s authorized militia and assumes the state mission of the Connecticut National Guard in the event the Guard is mobilized. The SDF comprises retired active and reserve military personnel and selected professional persons who volunteer their time and talents in further service to their state.\n\nConnecticut's state defense force consists of four active units known as the [[Governor's Guards]].  There are two foot guard units and two horse guard units which I preserve the lineage and heritage of Connecticut's infantry and cavalry units since [[Connecticut Colony|the colonial period]].  While all four companies are primarily ceremonial, the horse companies do drill in mounted search and rescue.<ref>Connecticut Military Department, [http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1348&Q=257236&milNav= State Militia Units] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013052229/http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1348&Q=257236&milNav= |date=2012-10-13 }}, accessed November 2011</ref>  The First Company of the Horse Guard was created in 1788 as the Independent Volunteer Troop of Horse Guards in [[Hartford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cslib.org/agencies/governorshorseguard1stco.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806003538/http://www.cslib.org/agencies/governorshorseguard1stco.htm |archivedate=2013-08-06 }}</ref>  A second Horse Guard company was created in 1808 in [[New Haven]].<ref>pp. 4-5 Katcher, Phillip & Volstad, Ron '' American Civil War Armies: Volunteer Militia'' 1989 Osprey Publishing</ref>  Both were created to serve and protect the governor between his travels between New Haven and Hartford.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/09/11/nyregion/horse-guard-to-settle-in-newtown.html | work=The New York Times | first=Charlotte | last=Libov | title=Horse Guard to Settle in Newtown | date=1988-09-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Connecticut State Guard Reserve is currently inactive.\n\n===[[Connecticut Naval Militia]]===\nThe Naval militia of the state remains an authorized force by state statute, but has been inactive for several decades with no current membership.\n\n==Agency history==\n[[File:Gov. Malloy in Afghanistan with Conn. troops (6352852057).jpg|thumb|Governor [[Dannel Malloy]] with troops in [[Afghanistan]]]]\nThe Agency traces its roots to May 11, 1637, when the [[Connecticut Colony|General Courts of the Colony of Connecticut]] established a military arm of the government.  This arm of the colony's government was responsible for overseeing and regulating the militiamen of the colony.  Agency personnel participated in several wars with [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]] as well as with and against European colonial powers.\n\nAfter the [[American Revolution]], the new [[State of Connecticut]] established the office of the [[Connecticut Adjutant General|Adjutant General]] in 1792 to oversee the [[Armed Forces of the State of Connecticut|Armed Forces of the State]].  Units of the [[Connecticut State Militia]] participated in all wars of the [[United States]].\n\nThe Connecticut Military Department was officially established as a state agency in 1939 by Chapter 345 of the Public Acts.  The act consolidated the office of the Adjutant General, the Quartermaster General, the Armory Board and the Armory Board Inspector.  In response to the coordination efforts of civil authorities to the [[Flood of 1955 (Connecticut)|Flood of 1955]] in which Governor [[Abraham Ribicoff]] mobilized the National Guard, the [[Connecticut Department of Emergency Management and Homeland Security|Office of Civil Defense]] was created as a sub-agency of the Connecticut Military Department.  Authority over the Office of Civil Defense was transferred to the Department of Public Safety in 1979 and back to the Military Department in 1999.  In 2005, Public Act 04-219 created the [[Connecticut Department of Emergency Management and Homeland Security]] and once again removed overall domestic emergency response away from the Military Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctstatelibrary.org/agencies/militarydepartment.htm|title=CT Military Department Agency History|publisher=CT State Library|accessdate=24 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225083852/http://www.ctstatelibrary.org/agencies/militarydepartment.htm|archivedate=25 December 2013}}</ref>  The Military Department remains as the largest force provider to the Governor during times of domestic emergencies.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal |Connecticut}}\n* [[Connecticut Adjutant General|List of Connecticut Adjutant Generals]]\n* [[Connecticut National Guard]]\n* [[Connecticut Air National Guard]]\n* [[Connecticut Army National Guard]]\n* [[Connecticut Naval Militia]]\n* [[Governor's Guards]]\n*[[List of decorations awarded by the United States National Guard#Connecticut|Awards of the Connecticut National Guard]]\n*[[List of United States militia units in the American Revolutionary War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n*[[United States Army Center of Military History]], [http://www.history.army.mil/ARNG/NG-CT.htm Bibliography of Connecticut Army National Guard History]\n*GlobalSecurity.org, [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/arng-ct.htm Connecticut Army National Guard], accessed 20 Nov 2006\n*{{cite web| last = Martin| first = Thaddeus| title = Connecticut National Guard| year = 2007| url = http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/| accessdate = 2007-02-28| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070128164746/http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/| archivedate = 2007-01-28}}\n\n{{NGbystate}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Military in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Connecticut National Guard]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Component of the US National Guard of the state of Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox government agency\n|agency_name   = Connecticut Military Department\n|logo          = [[File:Coat of Arms of the State of Connecticut.jpg|200px]]\n|logo_width    = \n|logo_caption  = Coat of arms of the state of Connecticut\n|seal          = \n|seal_width    = \n|seal_caption  = \n|formed        = 1939\n|preceding1    = \n|dissolved     = \n|superseding   = \n|jurisdiction  = [[Connecticut]]\n|headquarters  = [[Hartford, Connecticut|Hartford, CT]]\n|region_code   = \n|employees     = \n|budget        = \n|minister1_name  = \n|minister1_pfo   = \n|minister2_name  = \n|minister2_pfo   = \n|chief1_name     = Major General [[Francis J. Evon, Jr.|Francis J. Evon]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.ng.mil/ngbgomo/library/bio/862.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-12-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090805110716/http://www.ng.mil/ngbgomo/library/bio/862.htm |archive-date=2009-08-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|chief1_position = [[Connecticut Adjutant General|The Adjutant General]], Connecticut National Guard\n|chief2_name     = \n|chief2_position = \n|parent_department =\n|parent_agency = \n|child1_agency = [[Connecticut State Militia]]\n|website       = \n|footnotes     = \n|map       = \n|map_width = \n|map_caption = \n}}\nThe '''Connecticut Military Department''' is a state agency of the government of [[Connecticut]]. Its primary components are the \n[[Connecticut Army National Guard]], the [[Connecticut Air National Guard]], and four companies of the state militia. The Military Department of the [[State of Connecticut]] traces its origins to May 11, 1637, when the \"General Courts\" (colonial assembly - legislature) established a military arm of the provincial government. In 1939, the State's Military Department. was established to consolidate the offices of  [[Adjutant General]], [[Quartermaster General]], [[Armory (military)|Armory Board]], and Armory Board Inspector.<ref>per 1939 CGS Cum Suppl. sec. 215e. Military Dept. directs the Adjutant General.</ref>\n\n==Mission==\nThe Military Department of the State of Connecticut's principle public responsibility is to serve as the protector of American citizens of the State and their property in time of war, invasion, rebellion, riot or disaster. It serves as the main resource for the [[Governor of Connecticut|Governor]] in ensuring public safety in a variety of emergencies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1345&q=257166|title=CT Military Department Agency Information|publisher=CT Military Department|accessdate=24 December 2013|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113230443/http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1345&q=257166|archivedate=13 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Connecticut National Guard as the state militia also has a Federal Constitutional mission to support the [[President of the United States]] as Commander-in-Chief of the [[United States Armed Forces|Armed Forces of the United States]] and the [[United States Government|Federal Government]] in times of War or National Emergencies.\n\n==Components==\n\n===[[Connecticut National Guard]]===\nThe [[United States Constitution|Constitution of the United States]] specifically grants the U.S. Congress the power to \"raise armies.\" The U.S. Army, Navy, Air Force are armies raised under this provision. Additionally, the States, under the 2nd and 10th Amendments, have the right to raise their own armies, historically known as militias, today known as a State Defense Force (SDF). After the civil war, many states reduced funding for their militias and military training programs causing the threat of a reduction in war preparedness. As a result, Congress decided to raise a new federal army to be jointly administered by the states alongside the state defense forces: that army is known as the [[National Guard of the United States]]. Like the state militia/SDF, the National Guard is typically administered by the governors. Unlike the militia/SDF, the National Guard may be deployed abroad without the permission of the state governor, whereas the militia/SDF is under the exclusive authority of the states except in the rare event of invasion of the United States or domestic insurrection as specified in Article I Section 8 of the U.S. Constitution.\n\nThe Federal mission assigned to the National Guard is: \"To provide properly trained and equipped units for prompt mobilization for war, National Emergency or as otherwise needed.\"\n\nThe state mission assigned to the National Guard is \"To provide trained and disciplined forces for domestic emergencies or as otherwise provided by state law.\"\n \nThe Connecticut National Guard bestows a number of decorations for services to or on behalf of the state.\n\nMajor General [[Francis J. Evon, Jr.]] is the current [[Connecticut Adjutant General]] (TAG).\n\n====Connecticut Army National Guard====\nThe Connecticut Army National Guard was originally formed in 1672. During the [[War of 1812]], the [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] state government refused to place the state militia under control of the [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] national government, which resulted in friction, especially following British attacks on [[New London, Connecticut|New London]] and [[Stonington, Connecticut|Stonington]].\n\nAfter the American Civil War came to an end in 1865, a segregated company was raised in the Fifth battalion of the Connecticut National Guard so that men of color in [[New Haven]] could serve their state.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82015483/1882-08-09/ed-1/seq-2/|title=Presentation: Company A, Fifth Battalion, Presented with a Life Size Portrait of Captain J. H. Wilkins - Remarks of Ex and Present Officers|publisher=Morning Journal and Courier|website=Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers. Library of Congress.|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> Company A (1870-1919<ref>{{cite book|last=Saunders|first=Ernest|title=Blacks in the Connecticut National Guard: A Pictorial and Chronological History 1870 to 1919|date=1977|publisher=New Haven Afro-American Historical Society|publication-place=New Haven, Connecticut}}</ref>), bearing throughout its service monikers to honor its primary instigator, James H. Wilkins<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wikitree.com/wiki/Wilkins-4037|title=Major James H. Wilkins|website=WikiTree|last=Raymoure|first=K|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> - a sergeant with the famous [[54th_Massachusetts_Infantry_Regiment|54th Massachusetts Volunteer Infantry]] during the Civil War who bore the national flag at the [[Battle of Olustee]] - was also known as the ''Wilkins Guard''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn84027718/1900-03-22/ed-1/seq-3/|title=Obituary of James H. Wilkins|publisher=Connecticut Western News|website=Chronicling America: Historic American Newspapers. Library of Congress.|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>, the ''Wilkins Old Guard'', and the ''Wilkins Tigers''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ctdigitalnewspaperproject.org/2016/09/african-americans-in-the-ct-national-guard-1870-to-1919/|title=African Americans in the CT National Guard, 1870 to 1919|author=CT|website=Connecticut Digital Newspaper Project|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>.\n\nThe [[Militia Act of 1903]] organized the various [[U.S. state|state]] [[militia]]s into the present National Guard system.\n\nThe 102d Infantry Regiment fought with the [[26th Infantry Division (United States)|26th Infantry Division]] in World War I and then served with the [[43rd Infantry Division (United States)|43d Infantry Division]] from 1924 to 1951-52, including [[World War II]] and a deployment to [[West Germany]] during the [[Korean War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/1-102in.htm|title=1st Battalion, 102nd Infantry Regiment|first=John|last=Pike|website=www.globalsecurity.org|accessdate=26 April 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426182812/https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/1-102in.htm|archivedate=26 April 2018}}</ref> Other major historical regiments of Connecticut were the [[169th Infantry Regiment (United States)|169th Infantry Regiment]] and 192d Field Artillery.\n\nAfter 1968, the main formation in the state became the 43d Infantry Brigade of the [[26th Infantry Division (United States)|26th Infantry Division]].\n\nToday, the Connecticut Army National Guard is composed of approximately 5,000 soldiers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070128164746/http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/ |archivedate=2007-01-28 }}</ref>   It maintains facilities in 22 communities.  In 1999, these facilities included 22 armories, eight maintenance shops, four aviation facilities, four training site facilities.\n\nIts units include the 85th Troop Command, 143rd Area Support Group, 14th Civil Support Team (WMD), 248th Engineer Company, 250th Engineer Company, 143d and 643d Military Police Companies, 141st and 142d Medical Companies, the 143d Combat Service Support Battalion (formerly FSB), the 1109th Aviation Depot (AVCRAD), the 169th Regiment (RTI), and the [[192nd Military Police Battalion|192d Military Police Battalion]]. The primary combat unit is the 1st Battalion, 102d Infantry Regiment, assigned to the [[86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team (United States)|86th Infantry Brigade Combat Team]], which is headquartered in [[Vermont]].\n\n'''Aviation'''\n\nOne base is the Army Aviation Support Facility at [[Bradley International Airport]] where the 1st Battalion, 169th Aviation Regiment operate the CH-47F, UH-60A/L, HH-60M & C-12U<ref>https://portal.ct.gov/-/media/DAS/Communications/Communications-List-Docs/Digest/Digest-2015-2016/Military-Department.pdf</ref> The unit also operates Detachment 2, Company C, 3d Battalion, [[126th Aviation Regiment (United States)|126th Aviation Regiment]] (HH-60M)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20180610/nws09/180619946|title=New Connecticut National Guard medical helicopter unit set to deploy to Southwest Asia|publisher=The Day|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> and Company B, 2d Battalion (General Support), [[104th Aviation Regiment (United States)|104th Aviation Regiment]] (CH-47F)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ct.ng.mil/News/Pages/Connecticut-Army-National-Guard-Sends-Troops,-CH-47s-to-Support-Relief-Efforts.aspx|title=Connecticut Army National Guard Sends Troops, CH-47s to Support Relief Efforts|publisher=Connecticut National Guard|date=September 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====[[Connecticut Air National Guard]]====\n[[File:C-27J and C-21A of Connecticut ANG 2010.jpg|thumb|right|A C-21A of the Connecticut Air National Guard sits beside a C-27 during an Alenia familiarisation visit to Bradley ANGB]]\nThe [[Connecticut Air National Guard]] traces its history back to [[World War I]] with the beginnings also of the [[United States Army Air Service]]. It comprises approximately 1,200 airmen and officers assigned to the [[103d Airlift Wing|103rd Airlift Wing]] and 103rd Air Control Squadron. The [[103d Airlift Wing|103rd Airlift Wing]] is  based in [[East Granby, Connecticut|East Granby]] at the Bradley Air National Guard Base at [[Bradley International Airport]].\n\n[[File:F-100D 118th TFS Connecticut ANG 1976.JPEG|thumb|right|An F-100 of the Connecticut Air National Guard, 1976]]\nKnown as the \"Flying Yankees\", the [[103d Airlift Wing|103rd Airlift Wing]] is the third-oldest [[Air National Guard]] unit in the United States with a history dating back to World War I.<ref>Governor M. Jodi Rell (CT) (10 August 2005). [http://www.ct.gov/governorrell/cwp/view.asp?Q=300044&A=1761 Governor Rell Visits National Guard Fighter Wing Targeted Under BRAC Process] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110519170516/http://www.ct.gov/governorrell/cwp/view.asp?Q=300044&A=1761 |date=2011-05-19 }} Press Release.</ref> Until 2008, the organization was known as the 103rd Fighter Wing (103 FW), operationally gained by the [[Air Combat Command]] (ACC) and equipped with [[A-10 Thunderbolt]] aircraft.  As a result of [[Base Realignment and Closure]] (BRAC) actions, the wing's A-10 fighter aircraft were reassigned to other units and the 103rd reequipped with [[C-21 Learjet]] aircraft as a \"placeholder\" flying mission under the Air National Guard's VANGUARD<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oai.dtic.mil/oai/oai?verb=getRecord&metadataPrefix=html&identifier=ADA454806 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-05-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717145048/http://oai.dtic.mil/oai/oai?verb=getRecord |archivedate=2011-07-17 }}</ref> program until the 103rd's next flying mission could be determined.  Following this change in mission, the unit was redesignated the 103rd Airlift Wing and placed under the operational claimancy of [[Air Mobility Command]] (AMC).\n\nThe 103rd Air Control Squadron is based in [[Orange, Connecticut]],<ref name=CTANGSITE>{{cite web |url=http://www.ctbrad.ang.af.mil/ourmission.html |title=Our Mission |accessdate=2007-07-17 |work=Connecticut Air National Guard |publisher=U.S. Air Force |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070709094444/http://www.ctbrad.ang.af.mil/ourmission.html |archivedate=2007-07-09 }}</ref> and is known as \"Yankee Watch\". The mission of the 103rd Air Control Squadron is real-time detection, identification and surveillance of air traffic for combat operations and [[homeland defense]].  The 103rd ACS is the oldest unit of its kind in the United States military.<ref name=\"CTANGSITE\"/>\n\nThe Connecticut Air National Guard counts one [[astronaut]] amongst its former members, [[Jack Swigert]], who flew on [[Apollo 13]]. Swigert served with the CT ANG from April 1960 to October 1965.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html |title=Biographical Data - John L. Swigert, Jr. |accessdate=2007-07-19 |author=Astronaut Office of the Johnson Space Center |date=January 1983 |work=Johnson Space Center - Astronaut Biographies |publisher=NASA |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070320052948/http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/swigert-jl.html |archivedate=2007-03-20 }}</ref>\n\nBrigadier General Daniel L Peabody is the current Assistant Adjutant General-Air, for the CT ANG.\n\n===Connecticut State Guard===\nThe Connecticut State Guard is the organized militia portion of the state military. As a [[State Defense Force]] it is a military entity authorized by both the State Code of Connecticut and Executive Order. The State Defense Force (SDF) is the state\u2019s authorized militia and assumes the state mission of the Connecticut National Guard in the event the Guard is mobilized. The SDF comprises retired active and reserve military personnel and selected professional persons who volunteer their time and talents in further service to their state.\n\nConnecticut's state defense force consists of four active units known as the [[Governor's Guards]].  There are two foot guard units and two horse guard units which I preserve the lineage and heritage of Connecticut's infantry and cavalry units since [[Connecticut Colony|the colonial period]].  While all four companies are primarily ceremonial, the horse companies do drill in mounted search and rescue.<ref>Connecticut Military Department, [http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1348&Q=257236&milNav= State Militia Units] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121013052229/http://www.ct.gov/mil/cwp/view.asp?a=1348&Q=257236&milNav= |date=2012-10-13 }}, accessed November 2011</ref>  The First Company of the Horse Guard was created in 1788 as the Independent Volunteer Troop of Horse Guards in [[Hartford]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cslib.org/agencies/governorshorseguard1stco.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-02-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130806003538/http://www.cslib.org/agencies/governorshorseguard1stco.htm |archivedate=2013-08-06 }}</ref>  A second Horse Guard company was created in 1808 in [[New Haven]].<ref>pp. 4-5 Katcher, Phillip & Volstad, Ron '' American Civil War Armies: Volunteer Militia'' 1989 Osprey Publishing</ref>  Both were created to serve and protect the governor between his travels between New Haven and Hartford.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/09/11/nyregion/horse-guard-to-settle-in-newtown.html | work=The New York Times | first=Charlotte | last=Libov | title=Horse Guard to Settle in Newtown | date=1988-09-11}}</ref>\n\nThe Connecticut State Guard Reserve is currently inactive.\n\n===[[Connecticut Naval Militia]]===\nThe Naval militia of the state remains an authorized force by state statute, but has been inactive for several decades with no current membership.\n\n==Agency history==\n[[File:Gov. Malloy in Afghanistan with Conn. troops (6352852057).jpg|thumb|Governor [[Dannel Malloy]] with troops in [[Afghanistan]]]]\nThe Agency traces its roots to May 11, 1637, when the [[Connecticut Colony|General Courts of the Colony of Connecticut]] established a military arm of the government.  This arm of the colony's government was responsible for overseeing and regulating the militiamen of the colony.  Agency personnel participated in several wars with [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native Americans]] as well as with and against European colonial powers.\n\nAfter the [[American Revolution]], the new [[State of Connecticut]] established the office of the [[Connecticut Adjutant General|Adjutant General]] in 1792 to oversee the [[Armed Forces of the State of Connecticut|Armed Forces of the State]].  Units of the [[Connecticut State Militia]] participated in all wars of the [[United States]].\n\nThe Connecticut Military Department was officially established as a state agency in 1939 by Chapter 345 of the Public Acts.  The act consolidated the office of the Adjutant General, the Quartermaster General, the Armory Board and the Armory Board Inspector.  In response to the coordination efforts of civil authorities to the [[Flood of 1955 (Connecticut)|Flood of 1955]] in which Governor [[Abraham Ribicoff]] mobilized the National Guard, the [[Connecticut Department of Emergency Management and Homeland Security|Office of Civil Defense]] was created as a sub-agency of the Connecticut Military Department.  Authority over the Office of Civil Defense was transferred to the Department of Public Safety in 1979 and back to the Military Department in 1999.  In 2005, Public Act 04-219 created the [[Connecticut Department of Emergency Management and Homeland Security]] and once again removed overall domestic emergency response away from the Military Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctstatelibrary.org/agencies/militarydepartment.htm|title=CT Military Department Agency History|publisher=CT State Library|accessdate=24 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225083852/http://www.ctstatelibrary.org/agencies/militarydepartment.htm|archivedate=25 December 2013}}</ref>  The Military Department remains as the largest force provider to the Governor during times of domestic emergencies.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal |Connecticut}}\n* [[Connecticut Adjutant General|List of Connecticut Adjutant Generals]]\n* [[Connecticut National Guard]]\n* [[Connecticut Air National Guard]]\n* [[Connecticut Army National Guard]]\n* [[Connecticut Naval Militia]]\n* [[Governor's Guards]]\n*[[List of decorations awarded by the United States National Guard#Connecticut|Awards of the Connecticut National Guard]]\n*[[List of United States militia units in the American Revolutionary War]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official website}}\n*[[United States Army Center of Military History]], [http://www.history.army.mil/ARNG/NG-CT.htm Bibliography of Connecticut Army National Guard History]\n*GlobalSecurity.org, [http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/agency/army/arng-ct.htm Connecticut Army National Guard], accessed 20 Nov 2006\n*{{cite web| last = Martin| first = Thaddeus| title = Connecticut National Guard| year = 2007| url = http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/| accessdate = 2007-02-28| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070128164746/http://www.ct.ngb.army.mil/| archivedate = 2007-01-28}}\n\n{{NGbystate}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Military in Connecticut]]\n[[Category:State agencies of Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Connecticut National Guard]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Connecticut_Military_Department"}
{"title_page": "Confession", "text_new": "{{hatnote|See also: [[Confession (law)|Confessions in law]], [[Confession (religion)|Confessions in religion]], and [[Confession (disambiguation)]] and [[Confessions (disambiguation)]].}}\n{{redirect|Confess}}\n[[File:The Progress of Love - Love Letters - Fragonard 1771-72.jpg|thumb|''Confession of Love'' by [[Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard]] depicts a subject confessing feelings that had been concealed up to that point.]]\n\nA '''confession''' is a statement \u2013 made by a person or by a group of persons \u2013 acknowledging some personal fact that the person (or the group) would ostensibly prefer to keep hidden. The term presumes that the speaker is providing information that he believes the other party is not already aware of,<ref name=\"Shuy\">Roger W. Shuy, ''The Language of Confession, Interrogation, and Deception'' (1998), p. 2\u201310.</ref> and is frequently associated with an admission of a moral or legal wrong:\n{{quote|In one sense it is the acknowledgment of having done something wrong, whether on purpose or not. Thus confessional texts usually provide information of a private nature previously unavailable. What a sinner tells a priest in the confessional, the documents criminals sign acknowledging what they have done, an autobiography in which the author acknowledges mistakes, and so on, are all examples of confessional texts.<ref>Jorge J. E. Gracia, ''A Theory of Textuality: The Logic and Epistemology'' (1995), p. 94\u201395.</ref>}}\n\nNot all confessions reveal wrongdoing, however. For example, a confession of [[love]] is often considered positive both by the confessor and by the recipient of the confession, and is a common theme in literature.<ref>Giulio Marra, ''Shakespeare and this \"imperfect\" World: Dramatic Form and the Nature of Knowing'' (1997), p. 69, describing \"the distinction between \"to do\" and \"to confess\", between having thoughts of love and confessing one's love, between the indetermination of a feeling and its final definition\", as a theme that \"creeps into the various stories\".</ref><ref>Charles Emil Kany, ''The Beginnings of the Epistolary Novel in France, Italy and Spain'' (1937), Volume 21, Issues 1-6, p. 19.</ref> With respect to confessions of wrongdoing, there are several specific kinds of confessions that have significance beyond the social. A [[Confession (law)|legal confession]] involves an admission of some wrongdoing that has legal consequence, while the concept of [[Confession (religion)|confession in religion]] varies widely across various belief systems, and is usually more akin to a [[ritual]] by which the person acknowledges thoughts or actions considered [[sin]]ful or morally wrong within the confines of the confessor's religion. In some religions, confession takes the form of an [[oral communication]] to another person. Socially, however, the term may refer to admissions that are neither legally nor religiously significant.<ref name=\"Shuy\"/>\n\n== Psychology ==\nConfession often benefits the one who is confessing . [[Paul Wilkes]] characterizes confession as \"a pillar of mental health\" because of its ability to relieve [[anxiety|anxieties]] associated with keeping [[Secrecy|secrets]].<ref>\n{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/artofconfessionr0000wilk|url-access=registration|title=The Art of Confession: Renewing Yourself Through the Practice of Honesty|last1=Wilkes|first1=Paul|publisher=Workman Publishing|isbn=9780761168720|date=2012|page=xi|quote=Confession is also a pillar of mental health, for confession is about self-examination. It demands something for which there is no substitute: that we be honest with ourselves.|author-link1=Paul Wilkes}}<!--| accessdate            = 2015-07-27-->\n</ref>\nConfessants are more likely to confess when the expected benefits outweigh the marginal costs (when the benefit of the offense to them is high, the cost to the victim is low, and the probability of information leakage is high).<ref>\n{{cite journal|last1= Sznycer|first1= Daniel|last2= Schniter|first2= Eric|last3= Tooby|first3= John|last4= Cosmides|first4= Leda|title= Regulatory adaptations for delivering information: The case of confession|journal= Evolution and Human Behavior|volume= 36|issue= 1|pages= 44\u201351|date= 5 September 2014|doi= 10.1016/j.evolhumbehav.2014.08.008|pmid= 25663798|pmc= 4313746}}\n</ref> People may undertake social confessions in order to relieve feelings of guilt or to seek forgiveness from a wronged party, but such confessions may also serve to create social bonds between the confessant and the confessor, and may prompt the listener to reply with confessions of their own.<ref name=\"Shuy\"/> A person may therefore confess wrongdoing to another person as a means of creating such a social bond, or of extracting [[Reciprocity (social psychology)|reciprocal]] information from the other person.<ref name=\"Shuy\"/> A confession may be made in a self-aggrandizing manner, as a way for the confessant to claim credit for a misdeed for the purpose of eliciting a reaction to that claim.<ref name=\"Shuy\"/>\n\n==Law==\n{{main|Confession (law)|Statement against interest}}\nIn law, there is [[declaration against interest|an exception]] to the [[hearsay]] rule that allows testimony concerning someone else's confession to be admitted if the statement had a great enough tendency \"to expose the declarant to civil or criminal liability\". The theory is that a reasonable person would not make such a [[false confession]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.law.cornell.edu/rules/fre/rule_804|title= Rule 804. Hearsay Exceptions; Declarant Unavailable|author= |date= |work= LII / Legal Information Institute|access-date= 28 April 2016}}</ref> In U.S. law, a confession must be [[voluntariness|voluntary]] in order to be admissible.<ref>\n{{cite web\n|url= https://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/text/18/3501\n|title= 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 3501 - \n|author= |date= \n|work= LII / Legal Information Institute\n|access-date=28 April 2016\n}}\n</ref>\n\nConfessions (whether [[forced confession | forced]] or otherwise) may feature in formal or informal [[show trial]]s.<ref>\nNote for example:\n{{cite book\n| last1 = Cook\n| first1 = Alexander C.\n| chapter = Testimony\n| title = The Cultural Revolution on Trial: Mao and the Gang of Four\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=o4YHDgAAQBAJ\n| publisher = Cambridge University Press\n| date = 2016\n| page = 118\n| isbn = 9781316785096\n| access-date = 2017-09-08\n| quote = [...] there is no evidence, either in the available documents or in [[Wang Hongwen]]'s shallow personality, to suggest he arrived at his confession through a searching self-examination in the manner of [[Nikolai Bukharin]]'s elaborately conceived philosophical confession presented in his Stalin-era show trial.\n}}\n</ref>\n\n== Medicine==\n'''Dr. Suzanne Karan''', a residency program director at the University of Rochester Department of Anesthesiology and Perioperative Medicine, initiated confessions sessions in residency education. In 2015, Dr. Karan published her research on confessions and it was concluded that the use of confessions sessions provided an opportunity to reflect, discuss, and admit without fear of punitive actions and allowed for early intervention on the issues that are relevant to physician trainees (Karan, 2015).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Karan|first=Suzanne B.|last2=Berger|first2=Jeffrey S.|last3=Wajda|first3=Michael|date=2015|title=Confessions of Physicians: What Systemic Reporting Does Not Uncover|journal=Journal of Graduate Medical Education|volume=7|issue=4|pages=528\u2013530|doi=10.4300/jgme-d-15-00054.1|pmid=26692961|pmc=4675406|issn=1949-8349}}</ref> \n\n== Socialisation==\nPublic confessions play a role in [[struggle session]]s<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1 = Williams\n| first1 = Philip F.\n| author-link1 = \n| last2 = Wu\n| first2 = Yenna\n| chapter = The PRC Prison Camp (II): From Struggle Sessions to Release or Death\n| title = The Great Wall of Confinement: The Chinese Prison Camp Through Contemporary Fiction and Reportage\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=ybEwDwAAQBAJ\n| location = Berkeley\n| publisher = University of California Press\n| date = 2004\n| page = 115\n| isbn = 9780520244023\n| access-date = 2017-09-08\n| quote = During a 'study' session, the person receiving criticism usually makes a substantial verbal response of some sort. [...] In contrast, objects of a struggle session are typically expected to bow their heads contritely, bend forward at the waist, and succinctly confess their guilt ''[ren zui]''. [...] The required parts of the struggle session ritual include the stage or platform where the bowed objects of the strugle stand contritely next to gesticulating and slogan-shouting cadres or other leaders, along with the audience seated nearby, who parrot the slogans in a shouted refrain. For example, Song Shan remarks that all seventy-six times she was subjected to a struggle session in front of thousands of people, the format of the event was exactly the same.\n}}\n</ref>\nand in other methods of [[social control]] and influence involving [[self-criticism]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1 = Mead\n| first1 = George Herbert\n| author-link1 = George Herbert Mead\n| chapter = The Social Foundations and Functions of Thought and Communication\n| year = 1934\n| editor1-last = Morris\n| editor1-first = Charles W.\n| editor1-link = Charles W. Morris\n| title = Mind, Self, and Society: The Definitive Edition\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=22jtBwAAQBAJ\n| location = Chicago\n| publisher = University of Chicago Press\n| publication-date = 2015\n| page = 255\n| isbn = 9780226112879\n| access-date = 2017-09-08\n| quote = [...] through self-criticism, social control over individual behavior or conduct operates by virtue of the social origin and basis of such criticism. That is to say, self-criticism is essentially social criticism, and behavior controlled by self-criticism is essentiall behavior controlled socially.\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1 = Pennebaker\n| first1 = James W.\n| author-link1 = \n| chapter = 12: Confession in Context: Therapy Religion and Brainwashing\n| title = Opening Up: The Healing Power of Expressing Emotions\n| chapter-url = https://books.google.com/books?id=U2doiTNg134C\n| location = New York\n| publisher = The Guilford Press\n| date = 2012\n| page = 172\n| isbn = 9781462504848\n| access-date = 2017-09-08\n| quote = Confession also occurs outside religious institutions. Within political systems that actively discourage religion, such as offshoots of Marxism, forms of confession or self-criticism are fostered.\n}}\n</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Atonement in Judaism]]\n* [[Repentance]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wiktionary}}\n{{commonscat|Confession}}\n\n[[Category:Communication]]\n[[Category:Secrecy]]\n[[Category:Confession| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{hatnote|See also: [[Confession (law)|Confessions in law]], [[Confession (religion)|Confessions in religion]], and [[Confession (disambiguation)]] and [[Confessions (disambiguation)]].}}\n{{redirect|Confess}}\n[[File:The Progress of Love - Love Letters - Fragonard 1771-72.jpg|thumb|''Confession of Love'' by [[Jean-Honor\u00e9 Fragonard]] depicts a subject confessing feelings that had been concealed up to that point.]]\n\nA '''confession''' is a statement \u2013 made by a person or by a group of persons \u2013 acknowledging some personal fact that the person (or the group) would ostensibly prefer to keep hidden. The term presumes that the speaker is providing information that he believes the other party is not already aware of,<ref name=\"Shuy\">Roger W. Shuy, ''The Language of Confession, Interrogation, and Deception'' (1998), p. 2\u201310.</ref> and is frequently associated with an admission of a moral or legal wrong:\n{{quote|In one sense it is the acknowledgment of having done something wr