k/Marc Lazar/Gerhard Hirscher (eds.),Der Kommunismus in Westeuropa, Niedergang oder Mutation?, Landsberg/Lech, 1998, p. 477-497\n* Wehenkel, Henri/ Foetz, Guy/Hoffmann, Andr\u00e9, 1921-1981. Beitr\u00e4ge zur Geschichte der Kommunistischen Partei Luxemburgs, Luxembourg 1981\n* Wehenkel, Henri/Redondo, Jean-Laurent/Hoffmann, Andr\u00e9/Urbany, Serge, Table ronde: PCL et/ou nouvelle gauche: renouvellement et/ou scission, in: Cahiers Marxistes, No. 201, April-May 1996, p. 121-144\n== External links ==\n* {{Official|http://www.kp-l.org/}}\n* [http://www.zlv.lu/ ''Zeitung vum L\u00ebtzebuerger Vollek''], newspaper aligned with the Communist Party of Luxembourg\n\n{{Luxembourgian political parties}}\n\n[[Category:Political parties in Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Communist parties in Luxembourg|Communist Party of Luxembourg]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 1921]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country = Luxembourg\n| name = Communist Party of Luxembourg\n|native_name = Kommunistesch Partei vu L\u00ebtzebuerg\n| colorcode = red\n| logo = Kommunistesch Partei Letzebuerg Logo.svg\n| logo_size = 120px\n| leader = [[Ali Ruckert]]\n| foundation = 2 January 1921\n| split = [[Luxembourg Socialist Workers' Party]]\n| headquarters = 3, rue Z\u00e9non Bernard<br />[[Esch-sur-Alzette]]\n| newspaper = [[Zeitung vum L\u00ebtzebuerger Vollek]]\n| youth_wing =\n| position = [[Far-left]]\n| ideology = [[Communism]]<br />[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<br>[[Euroscepticism#Hard_Euroscepticism|Hard Euroscepticism]]\n|international = [[International Meeting of Communist and Workers' Parties]]<br />[[International Communist Seminar]]\n| seats1_title  = [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]]\n| seats1        = {{Composition bar|0|60|hex= {{Communist Party of Luxembourg/meta/color}}}}\n| seats2_title  = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats2        = {{Composition bar|0|6|hex= {{Communist Party of Luxembourg/meta/color}}}}\n| seats3_title = Local councils\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|2|600|hex= {{Communist Party of Luxembourg/meta/color}}}}\n| colours = [[Red]]\n| website = {{URL|http://www.kp-l.org}}\n}}\n{{Communist Parties}}\nThe '''Communist Party of Luxembourg''' ({{lang-lb|Kommunistesch Partei vu L\u00ebtzebuerg}}, {{lang-fr|Parti Communiste Luxembourgeois}}, {{lang-de|Kommunistische Partei Luxemburgs}}), abbreviated to '''KPL''' or '''PCL''', is a [[communist party]] in [[Luxembourg]].\n\n[[Ali Ruckert]] is the current chairman of the party.\n\n== History ==\nThe KPL was founded on 2 January, 1921, in the town of [[Niederkorn]], making it one of the oldest parties in Luxembourg. In 1937, the Bech government attempted to introduce the so-called ''[[Maulkuerfgesetz]]'' (\"Muzzle law\") which would have banned the party. The law was abandoned after failing to achieve popular support in a national referendum.\n\nFollowing the end of the [[Second World War]], the party, which won 11.1% in the legislative elections, joined the [[National Union Government (1945)|National Union Government]] (1945\u201347). Its first minister was [[Charles Marx]]. After Marx's death in a 1946 [[car accident]], he was replaced by [[Dominique Urbany]]. After the death of the leader of the [[Luxembourg Socialist Workers' Party|LSAP]], the coalition collapsed. With the principle of an all-inclusive government gone, the KPL was excluded from the next government and never returned another member to the cabinet.\n\nIn 1964, the [[United States]] [[United States Department of State|State Department]] estimated the party membership to be approximately 500.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Benjamin |first=Roger W. |author2=Kautsky, John H. |date=March 1968 |title=Communism and Economic Development |journal=American Political Science Review |volume=62 |issue=1 |pages=110\u2013123 |jstor=1953329 |doi=10.2307/1953329}}</ref> In [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1964|legislative elections]] held in the same year, the party registered 10.4% of the vote, and won five of the [[Chamber of Deputies of Luxembourg|Chamber of Deputies]]' 56 seats. The party's representation in the Chamber peaked at the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1968|following election]], with six deputies, but fell, until the KPL lost its last remaining deputy in [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1994|1994]]. In the same year a minority opposing the Marxist-Leninist line of the party split and founded the [[New Left (Luxembourg)|New Left]] ({{lang-lb|Nei L\u00e9nk)}} together with the rest of the [[Revolutionary Socialist Party (Luxembourg)|Revolutionary Socialist Party]] ({{lang-lb|Revolution\u00e4r Sozialistesch Partei}}).   \n\nIn 1999, the KPL and the New Left agreed to found [[The Left (Luxembourg)|The Left]] ({{lang-lb|D\u00e9i L\u00e9nk}}). The Left had members of both parties and independents. Accordingly, KPL members ran on The Left lists in the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 1999|1999]] and 2000 elections and no separate KPL lists existed. After disputes between a majority within the Left and leading KPL members shortly before the [[Luxembourgian legislative election, 2004|2004 elections]] the party again ran separate lists. A number of the Left members were subsequently expelled from the KPL.\n\nThe KPL is represented locally on the councils of [[Differdange]] and [[Rumelange]]. In Rumelange it is part of the ruling coalition together with the [[Luxembourg Socialist Workers' Party|LSAP]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://zlv.lu/spip/spip.php?article19924|title=R\u00fcmelingen: LSAP und KPL wollen neue Wege gehen|date=2017-11-30|website=Zeitung vum L\u00ebtzebuerger Vollek|access-date=2019-04-21}}</ref>. It is the only leftwing majority coalition in Luxembourg.\n\n==Election results==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Votes\n! %\n! Elected seats\n! Seats after\n! +/\u2013\n|-\n! [[Luxembourg general election, 1922|1922]]{{efn|name=Partial|Partial election. Only half of the seats were up for r